            . I live at the <placeName id="t18100919-108-crimeloc619">Sir Han Sloanes head public house, Knightsbridge</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18100919-108-crimeloc619" type="placeName" value="Sir Han Sloanes head public house, Knightsbridge"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18100919-108-crimeloc619" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18100919-108-off617 t18100919-108-crimeloc619"></join>. The prisoner was quartered at our house, my box was in the room where he slept. On the 28th of June, between nine and ten o'clock at night, I missed seven yards of linen cloth out of my box; in about half an hour after I missed it, I saw it at Mr. Chalmers, a pawnbrokers.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18100919-108-person907">
                  JOHN 
                  GOODEAR
               <interp inst="t18100919-108-person907" type="surname" value="GOODEAR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18100919-108-person907" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18100919-108-person907" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a servant to Mr. Chalmers, pawnbroker, at Knightsbridge. On the 28th of July, about ten o'clock in the evening, the prisoner pledged seven yards of linen, I lent him eight shillings on it; in about half an hour afterwards the prosecutor came and claimed it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The cloth was given to me by another man to pawn, an old man who has been drinking, and said he was a watchman. I have been serving my King and country thirty-five years; I never defrauded a man yet of a shilling.</p>
